      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Suprascapular neuropathy is caused by compression or traction of the nerve. Common causes include ganglion cysts from labral tears, repetitive overhead activities (volleyball, baseball), massive rotator cuff tears, and anatomical variations like a narrow suprascapular notch or ossified transverse scapular ligament."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How long is recovery after suprascapular nerve decompression?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Most patients return to sedentary work within 3-4 weeks. Return to heavy manual labor typically takes 3-4 months. Athletes generally return to competitive play within 3-8 months, with 92-98% returning to sport and 88-96% reaching their previous performance level."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Will my muscle recover after suprascapular nerve surgery?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
